T1  - Work Values and Organizational Commitment
AU  - Kidron, Aryeh
Y1  - 1978/06/01
PY  - 1978
DA  - 1978/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255757
DO  - 10.5465/255757
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 239
EP  - 247
VL  - 21
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Dubin, Champoux and Porter (1975) found a strong relationship between central life interests of workers and their commitment to the organization. This paper extends their findings by investigating the relationship between work values, defined as the Protestant Ethic of the worker, and commitment to the organization. A distinction is made between moral and calculative commitment, and it is show it that work values are related more to moral than calculative involvement.
AB  - Dubin, Champoux and Porter (1975) found a strong relationship between central life interests of workers and their commitment to the organization. This paper extends their findings by investigating the relationship between work values, defined as the Protestant Ethic of the worker, and commitment to the organization. A distinction is made between moral and calculative commitment, and it is show it that work values are related more to moral than calculative involvement.
